caption: Seattle Public Library's Columbia City branch celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2015. The facility has seen a major renovation and the addition of Marvin Oliver's 1992 sculpture "Spirit of Washington."  (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Columbia City is a historic and recently trendy neighborhood in the Rainier Valley in southeast Seattle. (Bettina Hansen/The Seattle Times)

The Columbia City Bakery, on Rainier Avenue South, is a bakery you can bike to and is a recommended detour for people riding along Lake Washington Boulevard in South Seattle.  (Mike Siegel / The Seattle Times)
The former Columbia City Cinem has been reopened as Ark Lodge Cinemas in Columbia City in Seattle.  (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
A runner strides along the circle walk in Bellevue’s Downtown Park. (John Lok / The Seattle Times)
Downtown Bellevue’s Old Main Street is a shopping destination in traditional Main Street style. (Greg Gilbert/The Seattle Times)
Downtown Bellevue is a shopping destination for many and is home to outdoor complexes and large malls, including Bellevue Square. (Steve Ringman / The Seattle Times)
Bellevue Art Museum, which grew out of an art fair, was founded in 1975. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Moviegoers gather in Capitol Hill’s Cal Anderson Park in 2014 to watch “Dirty Dancing,” presented by The Three Dollar Bill Outdoor Cinema. (Maddie Meyer/The Seattle Times)
The very popular Espresso Vivace sidewalk bar on Broadway, started as a cart and is now a bit more substantial. (Benjamin Benschneider / The Seattle Times)

One of the few monuments dedicated to the late rocker Jimi Hendrix is a statue on Broadway Avenue near Seattle Central Community College in Seattle. The statue, entitled "The Electric Lady Studio Guitar", was made by artist Daryl Smith.  (John Lok / The Seattle Times)
Everyday Music is a record store located across the street from Elliot Bay Book Co. on Capitol Hill.   (Sy Bean / The Seattle Times)
Capitol Hill Block Party is a three-day music festival that takes place during the summer in Seattle's Capitol Hill neighborhood. (Sophia Nahli Allison / The Seattle Times)
Adolf Schreyer's oil painting 'The Burning Stable' at the Frye Art Museum on First Hill. Entrance to the museum, which opened in 1952, is free of charge. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
St. James Cathedral, the cathedral for the Catholic Archdiocese of Seattle, is located in Seattle's First HIll neighborhood. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
Opened in 1908, the Sorrento Hotel, is a local landmark that has undergone a makeover. The renovation includes this remodeled restaurant, now called the Dunbar Room. (Mike Siegel / The Seattle Times)
The lake in Green Lake offers a 2.8-mile path for running, biking and walking. Various clubs have boating events and races on the lake. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Runners pass Daffodils as they take advantage of the Green Lake trail near Ashworth Avenue North. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
The neighborhood is home to the Green Lake Pitch 'n Putt, where the longest of the nine 3-par holes is 115 yards. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
An annual From Hiroshima to Hope event commemorating the anniversary of the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki is held in Green Lake.   (Lindsey Wasson / The Seattle Times)
Two large water towers can be seen in the High Point neighborhood of West Seattle. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)
Seattle's High Point neighborhood is home to the West Seattle Bee Garden, which is located adjacent to a P-Patch. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)

Neighborhood House  High Point Center Sunscreens over the windows at Neighborhood House’s High Point Center help reduce energy costs and add beauty to the building. Environmental Works, which has designed other Neighborhood House buildings, worked with the group on this one, too. (Benjamin Benschneider / The Seattle Times)
The commercial strip on Lake City Way NE offers quite a few options for budget dining, shopping and services. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Matthews Beach Park on Lake Washington in Lake City neighborhood offers a popular swimming spot in the summer, and great views all year round. (Mike Siegel / The Seattle Times)

A view of Lower Queen Anne from the Space Needle shows a mishmash of architecture including St. Paul's Episcopal Church, Counterbalance Park and the illustrious, 24-hour Metropolitan Market.   (Greg Gilbert / The Seattle Times)
Festival-goers enjoy the greenspace at Fountain Lawn Stage in Lower Queen Anne.   (Alan Berner / The Seattle Times)
SIFF offers an annual membership for discounted shows at their Uptown location (shown above in Lower Queen Anne neighborhood) and a Capitol Hill location. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)
Citizen is a mainstay cafe in Lower Queen Anne offering anytime-breakfast including the well-regarded Huevos Rancheros. (Dean Rutz / The Seattle Times)

The Seattle Monorail, which was built for the World's Fair in Seattle in 1962, runs on a one-mile route along Fifth Avenue from the Seattle Center to Westlake Center.The monorail travels through the Experience Music Project Museum at Seattle Center. The museum was built around the Monorail route.   (Ellen M. Banner / The Seattle Times)
Skaters were pretty stoked about the course and the views when the skatepark at Beacon Hill's Jefferson Park opened in 2012. (Lindsey Wasson / The Seattle Times)
PacMed Tower is Beacon Hill defining landmark, and can be seen from much of downtown and surrounding areas.   (Ellen M. Banner / The Seattle Times)
Beacon Hill's Baja Bistro Bar is famous for their chile relleno and their Wednesday night Drag Show.   (Lindsey Wasson / The Seattle Times)

Lake Union Wooden Boat Festival is held annually in Seattle at the Center for Wooden Boats. Visitors have access to free ship-building sessions, as well as the ability to tour all different kinds of crafts. (Marcus Yam / The Seattle Times)
The free-to-the public Center for Wooden Boats offers a Sunday Public Sail on South Lake Union.   (Lindsey Wasson / The Seattle Times)
Amazon's headquarters are located in the South Lake Union neighborhood of Seattle, though the tech giant has also been leasing in the Denny Triangle. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)
Seattle Urban Farm Company designed the vegetable and flower gardens on the rooftop deck of the Stackhouse Apartments in the South Lake Union neighborhood.   (Mike Siegel / The Seattle Times)
Boats are moored beneath the University Bridge as Seattle's University District neighborhood rises beyond. (Elaine Thompson / The Associated Press)
The University District Street Fair showcases local arts, music and food and is open to UW students and the community. (Alan Berner / The Seattle Times)
Pierce Lane in the University of Washington Quad showcases 30 Yoshino Cherry Trees that are are in their peak beauty for about two weeks every spring.  (Steve Ringman / The Seattle Times)
Suzzallo and Allen Libraries, also referred to as "the Harry Potter libraries" for their stately interior, are great resources for UW students. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
A view from inside of the beloved Easy Street Records in West Seattle Junction. (Greg Gilbert / The Seattle Times)
Shoppers pass by various vendors in the extensive, year-round West Seattle farmer's market. (Greg Gilbert / The Seattle Times)
The main strip of West Seattle Junction is a highly walkable area, with shops and services nestled next to each other on California Avenue SW. (Dean Rutz / The Seattle Times)
A man walks along the shore of Lake Washington early morning in Renton's Gene Coulon Memorial Beach Park. (Ellen M. Banner / The Seattle Times)
The Landing in Renton, a 46-acre mixed-use development off Interstate 405, is near downtown Renton and offers shopping, dining and fitness options. (Mark Harrison)
Josh Treat of Mount Vernon and his son Korban, 3, shout for Pete Carroll's attention at the annual Seattle Seahawks training camp in Renton. (Bettina Hansen / The Seattle Times)
The Renton Transit Center is a hub for buses located near downtown. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)
Thousands walk in Renton's Khalsa Day parade. Sikh men, and some women, wear turbans as one of five external articles of faith called the five Kakars. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)

JusMoni dances while DJing at Denny Triangle's Re-bar during Soul Fi where dance centers around social justice, anti-racism, queerness and "celebrating blackness" said organizer RC Brown. (Erika Schultz / The Seattle Times)
It’s the shape of the future as the Amazon “biospheres” come together on Lenora Street between Sixth and Seventh Avenues in Denny Triangle. (Ken Lambert / The Seattle Times)

The Seattle Center Monorail is the nation's first full-scale commercial monorail system and links downtown Seattle to Seattle Center. Here, it travels down the tracks above 5th Ave. in Denny Triangle. (Ellen M. Banner / The Seattle Times)
Views from Denny Triangle can be sweeping. Here's the downtown Seattle skyline looking northwest showing the Westin towers, Elliott Bay and the Olympic Mountains. (Mike Siegel / the Seattle Times)
